  <h2>When a ductless mini-split is the right tool</h2>
  <p>A <strong>mini-split installation</strong> is not a replacement for a well-designed central system in most homes; for whole-home comfort, our <a href="/services/hvac-installation-tampa/">HVAC installation</a> and <a href="/services/ac-replacement-tampa/">AC replacement</a> pages cover ducted systems. But for the specific problems ductless solves, nothing else comes close. These are the five scenarios where we recommend it without hesitation:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Garage conversion or workshop:</strong> a 12,000 BTU single-zone head turns a 400 sq ft garage into a usable office, gym, or shop for roughly $4,200 installed.</li>
    <li><strong>Sunroom or bonus room:</strong> a west-facing glass sunroom in <a href="/service-areas/lutz-home-air-conditioning-service/">Lutz</a> or <a href="/service-areas/new-tampa-heating-and-cooling/">New Tampa</a> can run 15 degrees hotter than the house. A dedicated 18,000 BTU head fixes what duct extension cannot.</li>
    <li><strong>Mother-in-law suite or ADU:</strong> the cleanest way to condition a 300 to 800 sq ft accessory unit without tying into the main system.</li>
    <li><strong>Addition or second story:</strong> a dedicated head keeps your original system in its sweet spot instead of overstretching the ductwork.</li>
    <li><strong>Whole-home ductless:</strong> for older homes with no ductwork, a 3 or 4-zone system conditions the whole house with zero duct construction.</li>
  </ul>

  <TrustBar />

  <h2>Tampa Bay sizing rules we actually use</h2>
  <p>Manufacturer charts assume national-average climate. Florida is not average, so we size for a 94-degree design day, 78-degree dew point, and 2,200 annual cooling hours. The head you need is usually one size larger than the square-footage chart suggests:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>9,000 BTU:</strong> 300 to 450 sq ft, a well-insulated bedroom or office with one exterior wall.</li>
    <li><strong>12,000 BTU:</strong> 450 to 650 sq ft, a living area with two exterior walls or an east-glass sunroom.</li>
    <li><strong>18,000 BTU:</strong> 700 to 950 sq ft, an open living-kitchen combo or a west-facing sunroom.</li>
    <li><strong>24,000 BTU:</strong> 950 to 1,300 sq ft, large open spaces, usually one zone in a multi-zone install.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>These are starting points, not quotes. The real load depends on ceiling height, insulation, windows, orientation, and internal heat gain, so we run a short Manual-J on every quote, the same calculation behind our <a href="/services/ac-installation-wesley-chapel/">Wesley Chapel AC installs</a>.</p>

  <InContentCTA
    heading="Got a room that never gets cool?"
